  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Consider the matrix
	<m>B = \begin{bmatrix} -2 \amp 1 \\ 4 \amp -2 \\ 2 \amp -1 \\
	\end{bmatrix}</m>.
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Find the matrix <m>A</m> so that
	      <m>q\left(\twovec{x_1}{x_2}\right) = 
	      \len{B\xvec}^2=q_A(\xvec)</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Find the maximum and minimum values of <m>q(\uvec)</m>
	      among all unit vectors <m>\uvec</m>
	      and describe the directions in which they occur.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      What does the minimum value of <m>q(\uvec)</m> tell you
	      about the matrix <m>B</m>?
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>q(\xvec) = |B\xvec|^2 = (B\xvec)\cdot(B\xvec) =
	      \xvec\cdot(B^TB\xvec)</m> so <m>A = B^TB=\begin{bmatrix}
	      24 \amp -12 \\
	      -12 \amp 6 \\
	      \end{bmatrix}</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      The maximum value is <m>30</m> in the direction
	      <m>\twovec{2/\sqrt{5}}{-1/\sqrt{5}}</m> and the minimum
	      value is <m>0</m> in the direction 
	      <m>\twovec{1/\sqrt{5}}{2/\sqrt{5}}</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      The minimum value of <m>0</m> says there is a vector
	      such that <m>q(\uvec) = |B\uvec|^2 = 0</m>, which means
	      that <m>B\uvec=0</m>.  So there is a nonzero vector that
	      is a solution to the homogeneous equations, which
	      implies that the columns of <m>B</m> are linearly
	      dependent.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
    <answer>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>A = B^TB=\begin{bmatrix}
	      24 \amp -12 \\
	      -12 \amp 6 \\
	      \end{bmatrix}</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      The maximum value is <m>30</m> in the direction
	      <m>\twovec{2/\sqrt{5}}{-1/\sqrt{5}}</m> and the minimum
	      value is <m>0</m> in the direction 
	      <m>\twovec{1/\sqrt{5}}{2/\sqrt{5}}</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      The columns of <m>B</m> are linearly
	      dependent.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Consider the quadratic form
	<me>
	  q\left(\threevec{x_1}{x_2}{x_3}\right) =
	  7x_1^2 + 4x_2^2 + 7x_3^2 - 2x_1x_2 -4x_1x_3-2x_2x_3.
	</me>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      What can you say about the definiteness of the matrix
	      <m>A</m> that defines the quadratic form?
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Find a matrix <m>Q</m> so that the change of coordinates
	      <m>\yvec = Q^T\xvec</m> transforms the quadratic form
	      into one that has no cross terms.  Write the quadratic
	      form in terms of <m>\yvec</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      What are the maximum and minimum values for
	      <m>q(\uvec)</m> among all unit vectors <m>\uvec</m>?
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      The matrix
	      <m>A = \begin{bmatrix}
	      7 \amp -1 \amp -2 \\
	      -1 \amp 4 \amp -1 \\
	      -2 \amp -1 \amp 7
	      \end{bmatrix}</m> has eigenvalues <m>3</m>, <m>6</m>,
	      and <m>9</m> so <m>A</m> is positive definite.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>Q=\begin{bmatrix}
	      1/\sqrt{2} \amp 1/\sqrt{3} \amp 1/\sqrt{6} \\
	      0 \amp -1/\sqrt{3} \amp 2/\sqrt{6} \\
	      -1/\sqrt{2} \amp 1/\sqrt{3} \amp 1/\sqrt{6} \\
	      \end{bmatrix}
	      </m>.  If <m>\yvec=Q^T\xvec</m>, then <me>
	      q_A(\xvec) = 9y_1^2 + 6y_2^2 + 3y_3^2\text{.}
	    </me>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      The maximum value is <m>9</m> and the minimum value is
	      <m>3</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
    <answer>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>A</m> is positive definite.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>Q=\begin{bmatrix}
	      1/\sqrt{2} \amp 1/\sqrt{3} \amp 1/\sqrt{6} \\
	      0 \amp -1/\sqrt{3} \amp 2/\sqrt{6} \\
	      -1/\sqrt{2} \amp 1/\sqrt{3} \amp 1/\sqrt{6} \\
	      \end{bmatrix}
	      </m> and <m>
	      q_A(\xvec) = 9y_1^2 + 6y_2^2 + 3y_3^2</m>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      The maximum value is <m>9</m> and the minimum value is
	      <m>3</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Explain why the following statements are true.
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      Given any matrix <m>B</m>, the matrix <m>B^TB</m> is a
	      symmetric, positive semidefinite matrix.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      If both <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are symmetric, positive
	      definite matrices, explain why <m>A+B</m> is a
	      symmetric, positive definite matrix.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      If <m>A</m> is a symmetric, invertible, positive
	      definite matrix, 
	      then <m>A^{-1}</m> is also.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      The matrix is symmetric because <m>(B^TB)^T = B^T(B^T)^T
	      = B^TB</m>.  If <m>\uvec</m> is an eigenvector having
	      unit length, then <m>q(\uvec) = \uvec\cdot(B^TB\uvec) =
	      \lambda</m> and <m>q(\uvec) = \uvec\cdot(B^TB\uvec) =
	      (B\uvec)\cdot(B\uvec) = |B\uvec|^2 = \lambda \geq 0</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      If <m>\xvec</m> is a nonzero vector, then
	      <m>q_{A+B}(\xvec) = \xvec\cdot((A+B)\xvec) =
	      \xvec\cdot(A\xvec) + \xvec\cdot(B\xvec) = q_A(\xvec) +
	      q_B(\xvec) \gt 0</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      In this case, we know that the eigenvalues of <m>A</m>
	      are all positive.  If <m>\lambda</m> is an eigenvalue of
	      <m>A</m>, then <m>1/\lambda</m> is an eigenvalue of
	      <m>A^{-1}</m> so <m>A^{-1}</m> is also positive definite.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
    
    <answer>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>q(\uvec) = 
	      |B\uvec|^2 = \lambda \geq 0</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      <m>q_{A+B}(\xvec) 
	      = q_A(\xvec) +
	      q_B(\xvec) \gt 0</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      The eigenvalues of <m>A^{-1}</m> are the reciprocals of
	      the eigenvalues of <m>A</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </answer>
    
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Determine whether the following statements are true or false
	and explain your reasoning.
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      If <m>A</m> is an indefinite matrix, we can't know
	      whether it is positive definite or not.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      If the smallest eigenvalue of <m>A</m> is 3, then
	      <m>A</m> is positive definite.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      If <m>C</m> is the covariance matrix associated with a
	      data set, then <m>C</m> is positive semidefinite.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      If <m>A</m> is a symmetric <m>2\times2</m> matrix and
	      the maximum and minimum values of <m>q_A(\uvec)</m>
	      occur at <m>\twovec10</m> and <m>\twovec01</m>, then
	      <m>A</m> is diagonal.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      If <m>A</m> is negative definite and <m>Q</m> is an
	      orthogonal matrix with <m>B = QAQ^T</m>, then <m>B</m>
	      is negative definite.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
	<ol marker="a.">
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      False.  We know that it is neither positive nor negative
	      definite.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      True.  This implies that <m>q_A(\uvec) \geq 3</m> for
	      all unit vectors <m>\uvec</m>.  Then for any other
	      vector <m>q_A(\xvec) =q_A(|\xvec|\uvec)= |\xvec|^2
	      q_A(\uvec) \gt 0</m>.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      True.  If <m>\lambda</m> is an eigenvalue with associated
	      unit eigenvector <m>\uvec</m>, then
	      <me>
		q_C(\uvec) = \uvec\cdot(C\uvec) =
		\frac1N\uvec\cdot(AA^T\uvec) =
		\frac1N(A^T\uvec)\cdot(A^T\uvec) = \frac1N|A^T\uvec|^2
		\geq 0\text{.}
	      </me>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      True.  The matrix <m>Q=\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\
	      0 \amp 1 \\
	      \end{bmatrix}</m> is the identity so <m>A = QDQ^T =
